{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 per component-KPI (using full series) and then identified groups that had at least one point above their global P95 within the incident window (2021-03-09 15:30:00 CST to 16:00:00 CST). The compact anomaly table shows many groups triggered in-window: Redis (multiple redis metrics), several JVM-HeapMemoryUsed for IG01/IG02/MG01/MG02, and Tomcat request-processing KPIs. Earliest anomaly timestamps in that sample vary (examples: MG01 JVM-HeapMemoryUsed at 15:30:00 CST, IG02 JVM-HeapMemoryUsed at 15:35:00 CST, IG01 at 15:42:00 CST, many Redis metrics and Tomcat request spikes at 15:59:00 CST). There are a large number of anomaly groups (summary shows ~1709 groups scanned and ~638 groups with anomalies), so we must prioritize components by anomaly prevalence and earliest occurrence to narrow candidates for root cause localization. Next, we should aggregate anomalies by component to find which components have the most anomalous KPIs, the earliest anomaly time per component, and the strongest deviation (severity) so we can pick top candidate(s) for trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the anomaly detection results stored in the kernel (the full anomalies table you produced), do the following (use the stored full anomalies table; do not recompute global thresholds):\n1) Aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id and compute these fields: component_name (cmdb_id), num_anomalous_kpis (count of distinct kpi_name with count_points_above_p95>0), total_anomaly_points_in_window (sum of count_points_above_p95 across its KPIs), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum of earliest_timestamp_above_p95 across its KPIs), max_exceed_ratio (maximum across its KPIs of max_value_in_window / p95_global). Also include sample_top_kpi (the kpi_name of the KPI that contributed to that max_exceed_ratio).\n2) Return a compact table of the top 10 components sorted by num_anomalous_kpis descending, then total_anomaly_points_in_window descending. Limit to top 10 rows and show columns: component_name, num_anomalous_kpis, total_anomaly_points_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_exceed_ratio, sample_top_kpi.\n3) Additionally, for the single top-ranked component (the first row in the returned table), list its top 10 anomalous KPIs sorted by count_points_above_p95 descending (show columns: kpi_name, count_points_in_window, count_points_above_p95, earliest_timestamp_above_p95, p95_global, max_value_in_window).\nKeep outputs compact and bounded (no full time series). Store full intermediate aggregates in kernel variables for the next step."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and metric- and trace-level anomaly detection across the dataset. Key findings so far: many metric KPIs across the system exceeded their global P95 inside the incident window (1709 groups scanned, ~638 with anomalies). Component-level aggregation highlighted Mysql01/Mysql02 as having many anomalous KPIs by count, but trace-level analysis showed no trace anomalies for MySQL or Redis. Trace anomalies are concentrated in IG and Tomcat components (IG01/IG02 and Tomcat01–04), with earliest trace anomalies at the start of the incident window (2021-03-09 15:30:00 CST). Traces show IG services experienced elevated self durations and elevated durations for calls to Tomcat services; both IG and Tomcat components therefore look faulty at the service level. To localize the root cause we must determine whether Tomcat instances themselves exhibited resource faults (CPU, JVM, memory, GC, disk) that could explain IG trace latency, or whether IG is the origin of the problem. The next step is to inspect Tomcat metric KPIs (resource KPIs and JVM/request KPIs) for severity and timing to decide whether Tomcat is the downstream faulty service in traces (thus the root cause) or whether IG is the primary root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, focus on components Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute the global P95(value) using the full series and total points. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window (2021-03-09 15:30:00 CST through 2021-03-09 16:00:00 CST) and for each group compute: count_points_in_window, count_points_above_p95 (value > p95_global), earliest_timestamp_above_p95 (first timestamp in window where value > p95), max_value_in_window, and exceed_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95_global (handle p95_global == 0). Return a compact table of groups where count_points_above_p95 > 0 with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_global, count_points_in_window, count_points_above_p95, earliest_timestamp_above_p95, max_value_in_window, exceed_ratio. Sort by exceed_ratio descending then count_points_above_p95 descending. Limit output to top 20 rows and also return how many Tomcat groups were scanned and how many had anomalies. Keep outputs compact (no raw series)."
}

